---
import MainLayout from "@layouts/MainLayout.astro";
import BaseLayout from "@layouts/BaseLayout.astro";
import PageHeader from "@components/PageHeader.astro";
import SectionHeader from "@components/SectionHeader.astro";
import SectionLinks from "@components/SectionLinks.astro";
---

<BaseLayout pageTitle="This is the index">
	<MainLayout>
		<PageHeader>HAM Radio License Exam Question Pool Browser</PageHeader>
		<div class="pl-4 border-l-blue-900 border-l-8">
			<p class="my-4">
				Here you can browse through all the questions in the question
				pools for each of the three different license classes.
			</p>
			<p class="my-4">
				Each exam has a pool of questions that are separated into <strong
					>subelements</strong
				>. Each subelement is then divided up into <strong
					>groups</strong
				>.
			</p>

			<SectionHeader>What Are Subelements?</SectionHeader>
			<p class="my-4">
				A subelement represents a major subject area within amateur
				radio, such as regulations, operating procedures, technical
				aspects, or radio wave propagation. Each subelement covers a
				distinct set of knowledge and skills required for operating a
				radio station effectively and safely. For example, the
				regulations subelement may cover topics like licensing
				requirements, frequency allocations, and station identification
				procedures.
			</p>

			<SectionHeader>What Are Groups?</SectionHeader>
			<p class="my-4">
				Within each subelement, questions are further organized into
				groups. These groups act as smaller subsets within the
				subelement and often represent specific topics or subtopics
				related to the broader subject area. For instance, within the
				technical subelement, there might be groups focused on
				electronics theory, antenna design, electrical safety, or radio
				equipment troubleshooting.
			</p>
		</div>

		<ul>
			<li class="my-4">
				<div class="border-b-2">
					<SectionHeader size="large">Technician Exam</SectionHeader>
				</div>
				<p class="my-4">
					The Technician Class license is the entry-level license in
					amateur radio. It grants operators the basic privileges
					necessary to communicate on amateur radio frequencies.
					Holders of this license have demonstrated knowledge and
					understanding of fundamental concepts such as radio
					regulations, basic operating procedures, and safety
					practices. Technicians have access to a wide range of VHF
					and UHF frequencies, enabling local and regional
					communication using handheld or mobile radios. This license
					level serves as an excellent starting point for newcomers to
					the amateur radio hobby, allowing them to gain practical
					experience while exploring various aspects of radio
					communication.
				</p>
				<SectionLinks examName="technician" />
			</li>
			<li class="my-4">
				<div class="border-b-2">
					<SectionHeader size="large">General Exam</SectionHeader>
				</div>
				<p class="my-4">
					The General Class license represents an intermediate level
					of proficiency in amateur radio. Operators who hold this
					license have a deeper understanding of radio theory,
					regulations, and operating practices. The General Class
					license expands the privileges available to operators,
					providing access to a broader range of frequencies,
					including long-distance HF bands. With increased privileges,
					General Class operators can engage in long-range
					communication, utilize more powerful equipment, and explore
					various modes of operation such as voice, digital, and Morse
					code. This license level offers greater flexibility and
					opportunities for experimentation, making it a significant
					step forward for amateur radio enthusiasts seeking enhanced
					capabilities.
				</p>
				<SectionLinks examName="general" />
			</li>
			<li class="my-4">
				<div class="border-b-2">
					<SectionHeader size="large">
						Amateur Extra Exam
					</SectionHeader>
				</div>
				<p class="my-4">
					The Extra Class license is the highest level of amateur
					radio licensing. Holders of this license possess a
					comprehensive knowledge of radio regulations, advanced
					operating techniques, and in-depth understanding of
					electronics theory. Extra Class operators have access to all
					amateur radio frequencies, including exclusive segments,
					enabling them to communicate globally and utilize high-power
					transmitters. This license level reflects a commitment to
					excellence and signifies expertise in the field of amateur
					radio. Extra Class operators often engage in activities such
					as contesting, experimentation, and technical innovations,
					contributing to the advancement of the hobby as a whole.
				</p>
				<SectionLinks examName="extra" />
			</li>
		</ul>
	</MainLayout>
</BaseLayout>
